explanation:
1) toxdigitvalue — The function’s only call is toxdigitvalue(str[i]). Whether the while-loop is ever entered and whether the loop body (including the overflow-check branch and the res update) is reachable depends entirely on the values returned by toxdigitvalue for input bytes (i.e. which inputs yield >=0 and which yield -1). To determine if any code in MHD_strx_to_uint64_n_ is statically unreachable you must have the implementation or precise specification/contract of toxdigitvalue (return range and conditions).

2) UINT64_MAX — The overflow-check branch uses expressions involving UINT64_MAX (/16 and %16). To decide if the overflow-return branch can be taken (and thus whether that branch is reachable) you need the actual numeric value of UINT64_MAX as used in the build (macro definition). This lets you evaluate whether the conditional comparing res and digit can ever become true for any possible res/digit combination produced at runtime.
